        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(queue): persist followup queues across gateway restarts",
        "body": "## Problem\n\nWhen the gateway process restarts, followup messages queued during an active agent turn are silently lost.\n\n## Solution\n\nPersist followup queues in shared SQLite (`followup_queue_entries`), migrate legacy JSON sidecars via doctor, rehydrate from live config, and wake restored routes on gateway startup so production idle-kick can drain them.\n\nClassify `followup-queue-restore` heartbeats as wake payloads so empty/comment-only `HEARTBEAT.md` cannot skip restored-queue system events before drain.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: Followup messages queued during an active Telegram turn survive gateway restart and are delivered afterward instead of disappearing; restored-queue recovery heartbeats also bypass `HEARTBEAT.md` idle gating so valid restored sessions outside the routine heartbeat map still drain.\n- Real environment tested: Local machine `joseph-MS-7B51`, systemd `openclaw-gateway.service`, Telegram DM chatId `6300969793`, sessionKey `agent:main:telegram:slash:6300969793`.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch:\n  1. Start a live Telegram DM turn so the first agent reply is still in flight.\n  2. Send a second Telegram message in the same DM so it is queued as a followup behind the active turn.\n  3. Restart the gateway with `systemctl --user restart openclaw-gateway.service` while that followup is still pending.\n  4. Let gateway startup restore followup queue state from shared SQLite and request the recovery heartbeat wake.\n  5. Confirm the restored queue drains and the queued followup is delivered exactly once back to the same Telegram DM.\n- Evidence after fix:\n  - Earlier live Telegram proof from the same user-facing workflow remains valid for the delivered behavior: the restored followup prompt text was reloaded from persisted queue state and sent back to Joseph's Telegram DM after gateway restart.\n  - Copied live output / runtime evidence from that run included redacted journal lines like:\n\n    ```text\n    [followup-queue-recovery] requested heartbeat wake for 1 restored followup queue route(s)\n    [followup-queue-recovery] restored followup queue for route telegram:6300969793\n    Telegram outbound send confirmation for Joseph's DM after restart/drain\n    ```\n\n  - Current-head local validation on `a94470581b3cf10c0939b1fc6442c0431cfd0473` also passed:\n    - `pnpm lint --threads=8`\n    - `pnpm tsgo:prod`\n    - `pnpm check:test-types`\n    - targeted queue persistence / restart Vitest coverage\n- Observed result after fix: After restart, the queued Telegram followup is no longer silently lost. The queue is restored, recovery wake runs, and the pending followup drains back to the original DM route; the rebuilt head also keeps backward-compatible restore behavior for persisted rows missing newer summary fields.\n- What was not tested: A brand-new final-head live Telegram capture was not re-recorded after the `a94470581b3cf10c0939b1fc6442c0431cfd0473` force-push. The proof above is the same real workflow evidence, and the current head was revalidated locally with lint, prod types, test types, and targeted restart/persistence tests.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nCurrent head `a94470581b3cf10c0939b1fc6442c0431cfd0473` (local, June 15, 2026):\n\n```bash\nnode scripts/run-tsgo.mjs -p tsconfig.core.json --incremental --tsBuildInfoFile .artifacts/tsgo-cache/core.tsbuildinfo\n./node_modules/.bin/oxlint \\\n  src/infra/heartbeat-runner.ts \\\n  src/infra/heartbeat-runner.scheduler.test.ts \\\n  src/auto-reply/reply/queue/drain.ts \\\n  src/infra/state-migrations.ts\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs \\\n  src/gateway/server-followup-queue-recovery.test.ts \\\n  src/gateway/server-runtime-services.test.ts\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs \\\n  src/infra/heartbeat-runner.scheduler.test.ts \\\n  src/infra/heartbeat-runner.returns-default-unset.test.ts\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs \\\n  src/infra/followup-queue-sqlite.test.ts \\\n  src/infra/state-migrations.test.ts\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs \\\n  src/auto-reply/reply/queue/persist.test.ts \\\n  src/auto-reply/reply/queue.drain-restart.test.ts \\\n  src/auto-reply/reply/queue.followup-restart-roundtrip.test.ts\n```\n\nResults:\n- `tsgo:core`: passed\n- focused oxlint on the rebased repair surface: passed\n- gateway shard: **4 files, 24 tests passed**\n- heartbeat recovery shard: **2 files, 64 tests passed**\n- SQLite + migration shard: **2 files, 12 tests passed**\n- queue persist / restart / round-trip shard: **3 files, 38 tests passed**\n\n## Notes\n\n- The old dirty PR branch was preserved separately before the clean replay; the live PR branch now points at the rebuilt queue-only branch.\n- The earlier stale proof section referenced the pre-fix head `926f9538f501d4ca504b3a8a62e01827b7796ac9`; this body now reflects the current PR head `a94470581b3cf10c0939b1fc6442c0431cfd0473` and includes the required proof fields for the present branch state.\n",
